### A

*   [Aaron of Alexandria](/Aaron_of_Alexandria). A physician. Active in the 7th century. His writings, apparently, got translated into Arabic and Syriac. Later used by al-Razi. So, he’s in their orbit. Not exactly a glowing endorsement.

*   [Abdollah ibn Bukhtishu](/Abdollah_ibn_Bukhtishu). A Syriac physician, 940–1058. Another name on the roster. [1]

*   [Athanasius II Baldoyo](/Athanasius_II_Baldoyo). Syriac Orthodox historian. Patriarch of Antioch. Sounds important. Or at least, he was. [2]

*   [Ammar al-Basri](/Ammar_al-Basri). 9th-century East Syrian theologian. And an apologist. Defending his faith, I suppose, in a world that wasn't always inclined to listen. [3]

*   [Anthony of Tagrit](/Anthony_of_Tagrit). 9th-century West Syrian. Syriac theologian and a rhetorician. Someone who could string words together. Presumably in a way that mattered. [4]

*   [Abdisho bar Berika](/Abdisho_bar_Berika). Died 1318. A Syriac writer. And a bishop. So, both words and authority. [5]

### B

*   [Bukhtishu](/Bukhtishu). A family. Syriac Christian physicians. Spanning the 7th to 9th centuries. A lineage of healers. [6] [7] [8] [9]

*   [ibn Batriq](/Eutychius_of_Alexandria). Also known as Eutychius of Alexandria. 877–940. Physician. And a Melkite Patriarch of Alexandria. A double threat, perhaps. [10]

*   [Ibn Butlan](/Ibn_Butlan). Active around 1038 and 1075. An Arab Nestorian Christian physician. Quite the descriptor. [11]

*   [Abu Bishr Matta ibn Yunus](/Abu_Bishr_Matta_ibn_Yunus). 870 – June 20, 940. A Nestorian Christian philosopher. And a translator. Someone who bridged gaps. Philosophically, at least. [12]

### D

*   [Dionysius I Telmaharoyo](/Dionysius_I_Telmaharoyo). Died 845. Syriac Orthodox historian. Patriarch of Antioch. Another one holding a significant title. [13]

### G

*   [Gerasimos, Abbot of the Monastery of Saint Symeon](/Gerasimos,_Abbot_of_the_Monastery_of_Saint_Symeon). Active somewhere between the 9th and 13th centuries. A Christian apologist. Knowledgeable, they say. Which implies he knew things others didn't. Or chose not to.

### H

*   [Hunayn ibn Ishaq](/Hunayn_ibn_Ishaq). 809–873. An Arab Christian scholar. A physician. And a scientist. A busy man. Important for translating Greek texts into Arabic. Essential work, I suppose, if you care about that sort of thing. [14] [15] [16]

### I

*   [Ishaq ibn Hunayn](/Ishaq_ibn_Hunayn). Circa 830 – circa 910–11. Son of Hunayn, I presume. Arab Christian physician. And a translator. Continuing the family tradition.

*   [Ishodad of Merv](/Ishodad_of_Merv). Flourished around 850 AD. Syriac theologian. A writer. Someone who put their thoughts down on paper. Or parchment. [17]

### J

*   [Jabril ibn Bukhtishu](/Jabril_ibn_Bukhtishu). 8th century. Nestorian physician. Part of that medical dynasty. [18]

*   [Jacob Bar-Salibi](/Jacob_Bar-Salibi). He’s noted as the most prolific writer in the Syriac Orthodox Church during the twelfth century. Prolific. That means he wrote a lot. Presumably, it was read. [19]

*   [Jacob of Edessa](/Jacob_of_Edessa). Circa 640 – June 5, 708. Syriac apologist. And a philosopher. Someone who debated ideas. [20]

*   [Job of Edessa](/Job_of_Edessa). Natural philosopher. Physician. Active in Baghdad and Khurāsān. Under the Abbasid Caliphate. He played a role in getting Greek science to the Islamic world. Through Syriac translations. So, a conduit.

*   [John III of the Sedre](/John_III_of_the_Sedre). A theologian. [21]

*   [John bar Penkaye](/John_bar_Penkaye). 7th century historian. A chronicler of events. [22]

### K

*   [Abu Yûsuf ibn Ishâq al-Kindī](/Apology_of_al-Kindy). An Arab Christian scholar. And an Apologist. So, defending points of view.

### M

*   [Masawaiyh](/Masawaiyh). Circa 777–857. Nestorian Christian physician. Another one from the medical circles. [23] [24]

*   [Abu Sahl 'Isa ibn Yahya al-Masihi](/Abu_Sahl_%27Isa_ibn_Yahya_al-Masihi). Persian Christian physician. His lineage is noted as being of Iranian Christians. [25]

*   [Masawaih al-Mardini](/Masawaih_al-Mardini). Nestorian Christian physician. More medical expertise. [26]

*   [Michael the Syrian](/Michael_the_Syrian). Died 1199 AD. Syriac Orthodox Chronologist. And Patriarch of Antioch. A historian of time, it seems. [27]

### N

*   [Nastulus](/Nastulus). Just a name. No further elaboration. Intriguing. [28]

### Q

*   [Qusta ibn Luqa](/Qusta_ibn_Luqa). 820–912. Syrian Melkite physician. Scientist. Translator. A Renaissance man, of sorts, in that era. [29]

*   [Ibn al-Qilai](/Gabriel_ibn_al-Qilai). 1447–1516. Lebanese Maronite. Historian. Theologian. Poet. A multi-talented individual.

### R

*   [Ishaq bin Ali al-Rohawi](/Ishaq_bin_Ali_al-Rohawi). 9th-century Arab physician. Authored the first book on medical ethics in Arabic medicine. Ethics. How quaint. [30]

*   [Abu Raita al-Takriti](/Abu_Raita_al-Takriti). Syriac Orthodox theologian. And apologist. Another defender. [31]

### S

*   [Shapur ibn Sahl](/Shapur_ibn_Sahl). Died 869 AD. Persian Christian physician. From the Academy of Gundishapur. A renowned medical institution. [32]

*   [Salmawaih ibn Bunan](/Salmawaih_ibn_Bunan). Died 840. Assyrian Nestorian Christian physician. And translator. [33]

*   [Serapion the Younger](/Serapion_the_Younger). Just the name. No details. Another enigma.

*   [Sahl ibn Bishr](/Sahl_ibn_Bishr). Circa 786–845? Syriac Christian astrologer. Astronomer. Mathematician. A man of the stars and numbers. [34]

### T

*   [Ibn al-Tilmīdh](/Ibn_al-Tilm%C4%ABdh). 1074–1165. Syriac Christian physician. Pharmacist. Poet. Musician. Calligrapher. A veritable polymath. [35]

*   [Theodosius Romanus](/Theodosius_Romanus). Died June 1, 896. Syriac Orthodox translator. Patriarch of Antioch. Another translator with a high title.

*   [Theodore Abu Qurrah](/Theodore_Abu_Qurrah). Circa 750 – circa 823. Orthodox Christian theologian. And writer. [36]

*   [Thomas of Marga](/Thomas_of_Marga). 9th century. East Syrian bishop. Author of a significant monastic history in Syriac. He wrote about monks. Fascinating.

### U

*   [Ibn Uthal](/Ibn_Uthal). 7th-century Arab Christian physician. [37]

### Y

*   [Yahya ibn Sarafyun](/Yahya_ibn_Sarafyun). 9th century. Syriac physician.

*   [Yuhanna ibn Bukhtishu](/Yuhanna_ibn_Bukhtishu). 9th century. Nestorian Christian physician. Another member of that prominent family. [38]

*   [Yahya Ibn al-Batriq](/Yahya_Ibn_al-Batriq). Syrian astronomer. And translator. Involved in the celestial and the textual. [39]

*   [Yahya ibn Adi](/Yahya_ibn_Adi). 893–974. Syriac Jacobite philosopher. Theologian. Translator. A trifecta of intellectual pursuits. [40]

### Z

*   [Ibn Zur'a](/Ibn_Zur%27a). 943–1008. Syriac Jacobite Christian physician. And philosopher. A blend of science and thought.

